SIMPLE: sap
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sap
<hw>Sap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>saep</ets>; akin
to OHG. <ets>saf</ets>, G. <ets>saft</ets>, Icel. <ets>safi</ets>; of
uncertain origin; possibly akin to L. <ets>sapere</ets> to taste, to be
wise, <ets>sapa</ets> must or new wine boiled thick. Cf. <er>Sapid</er>,
<er>Sapient</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The juice of plants of any
kind, especially the ascending and descending juices or circulating
fluid essential to nutrition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The ascending is the <xex>crude</xex> sap, the
assimilation of which takes place in the leaves, when it becomes the
<xex>elaborated</xex> sap suited to the growth of the plant.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The sapwood, or alburnum, of a tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A simpleton; a saphead; a milksop.</def>
<mark>[Slang]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sap ball</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>any large
fungus of the genus Polyporus. See <er>Polyporus</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Sap green</b></col>, <cd>a dull light green pigment prepared
from the juice of the ripe berries of the <spn>Rhamnus
catharticus</spn>, or buckthorn. It is used especially by water-color
artists.</cd> -- <col><b>Sap rot</b></col>, <cd>the dry rot. See under
<er>Dry</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sap sucker</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>any one of several species of small American woodpeckers of the
genus <gen>Sphyrapicus</gen>, especially the yellow-bellied woodpecker
(<spn>Sphyrapicus varius</spn>) of the Eastern United States. They are
so named because they puncture the bark of trees and feed upon the sap.
The name is loosely applied to other woodpeckers.</cd> -- <col><b>Sap
tube</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a vessel that conveys
sap.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sap
<hw>Sap</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sapped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sapping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>saper</ets> (cf. Sp.
<ets>zapar</ets>, It. <ets>zapare</ets>), fr. <ets>sape</ets> a sort of
scythe, LL. <ets>sappa</ets> a sort of mattock.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To subvert by digging or wearing away; to mine; to undermine; to
destroy the foundation of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor safe their dwellings were, for <qex>sapped</qex> by
floods,⟦br⟧
Their houses fell upon their household gods.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To pierce with saps.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make unstable or infirm; to unsettle; to
weaken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ring out the grief that <qex>saps</qex> the mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sap
<hw>Sap</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To proceed by mining,
or by secretly undermining; to execute saps.</def> <rj><au>W. P.
Craighill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Both assaults are carried on by <qex>sapping</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sap</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sap
<hw>Sap</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>A narrow ditch or
trench made from the foremost parallel toward the glacis or covert way
of a besieged place by digging under cover of gabions, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sap fagot</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a fascine
about three feet long, used in sapping, to close the crevices between
the gabions before the parapet is made.</cd> -- <col><b>Sap
roller</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a large gabion, six or seven
feet long, filled with fascines, which the sapper sometimes rolls along
before him for protection from the fire of an enemy.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sapadillo</ent>⟦br⟧
